^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, now despite the fact they went down, there was a lot of underbidding here. First of all let us discuss whether Eddy should Michaels or bid 1S. You can make a case for either. Some people play "good/bad" Michaels, where you Michaels with less than 10 or more than 16. The idea being you pass with the bad hand and raise partner with the good hand. I am personally not a big fan. Eddy's hand is worth 16 Bergen Starting Points and 1S is fine.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT|^B@2
anda42:  Howard, are you saying you are not a fan of bad/good Michaels or of Michaels in general?|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I like Michaels. I don't think good/bad makes that much sense. Since, in competitive auctions, I use the law (LOTT), knowing how many cards you have in suits is more important to me than HCP. That is why I don't particularly care for good/bad. I would probably Michaels with Eddy's hand, but 1S is certainly a fine bid.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT|^B@2
FM75: So, do you always bid conventional 5-5 in competition? If not, how do you decide?|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I always try to show 5/5 in competition. The only time I do not is if one suit is a lot better than the other. For example if I had say AKQxx Qxxxx Kx x, I probably would bid 1S rather than Michaels. But, generally speaking I like to show my distribution if I can.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, back to Kerrie's bidding who has a bit of a problem. She has 11 HCP, so 2S is a bit of an underbid. Even assuming the King of clubs was not suspect, I like to play a cue bid promises 4 card support, although many do it with 3. So, even if the King of clubs were, say a red king, she still has a problem. 2S is too weak, but 2C promises 4 card support. I would probably lie and bid 2C if I had Kerrie's hand with a red king. But, given the hand she had, 2S is a reasonable compromise.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's look at Eddy's points. Once Kerrie raises spades, his hand is huge. He already had 16 Starting Points, and now he can add 2 for the singleton and 1 for the outside 4+ card heart suit for 19 Bergen Declarer points, it certainly is worth at least a raise to 3. I would have bid 4. And without heart ruffs, 4 makes easily, even if Kerrie's K of clubs was the 3 of clubs.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||NT|^B@2
hope: Should I have bid 3C instead of 3D after your double.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|3D is the correct bid, with 5 diamonds. I might only have 4 clubs, but it is likely I have at least 3 diamonds.|
