cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Slam is not particularly a good contract. You have to play the club suit for one loser and pick up the hearts for no losers. I would guess it is around 25% at best. However, I do think the bidding should be somewhat different. Over 2H, Kerrie has a good hand. Let's count her Bergen Declarer Points. She has 16 Starting Points--14 HCP, 1 quality suit, and 1 length. Once Nada raises hearts she can add 2 for the singleton and 1 for the outside diamond suit for 19 Declarer Points.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The partnership is in slam range if Nada has 14 or more Bergen Dummy Points. Nada has 13 Dummy points--13 HCP, minus 1 for dubious Qx of diamonds, and plus 1 for one doubleton--just a tad short. On close slams I use the following guideline:
^CIf I have an 8 card fit, I do not bid close slams;
^CIf I have a 9 card fit, I tend to be more aggressive.|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Essentially I add a point for the 9th trump. It often makes a big difference. So, even if Kerrie bids 3H, I only bid 4H with Nada's hand, as it is a pretty bare minimum. The only good thing is the 2 Aces which are useful in slam. But the Jack of spades may not be useful, and the hand is flat. So, they ended up in the right place.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In other words, Kerrie should bid 3H, which is a slam try, not 4H. Once she bids 2D, you are in a game force. By the principal of fast arrival, 3H by Kerrie is stronger than 4H. But even if Kerrie bids 3H, with her hand Nada should bid 4H. Further, once Kerrie raises hearts, NT is out of the picture.|
